    "guidance": "Every AI model is stateless by default — it has no memory of previous messages unless you send them. To simulate a conversation, pass an array of message objects where each object has a 'role' and 'content'.\n\nThe three roles are:\n• system — Sets the AI's persona, rules, and instructions. Sent once at the start.\n• user — Messages from the human.\n• assistant — Previous AI responses you want the model to remember.\n\nThis pattern is the foundation of all chatbots. You manage the history array yourself — append each user message and AI response, then pass the full array on each call.\n\nFor automatic history management, see the Memory samples (016–018).",
    "output": "BoxLang supports several data types out of the box:\n\n**Primitives:**\n- String — \"Hello, World!\"\n- Numeric — integers and floating-point (1, 3.14)\n- Boolean — true / false\n- Date/Time — date objects with full date manipulation\n\n**Complex Types:**\n- Struct — key/value pairs: { name: \"Luis\", age: 30 }\n- Array — ordered list: [1, 2, 3]\n- Query — tabular data (think ResultSet)\n\n**Special:**\n- Null — null or javaCast(\"null\", \"\")\n- Closure / Lambda — function references\n- Class instances\n\nBoxLang uses dynamic typing, so you rarely need to declare types explicitly.",
